Modeling and prediction for movies

Setup

Load packages

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(statsr)
library(GGally)

Load data

load("movies.Rdata")

Part 1: Data

The data set is comprised of 651 randomly sampled movies produced and released before 2016. Since random sampling was used, any conclusion form the data can be gerneralized to all movies producted and released before 2016.
Since we can not find random assignment was used, we can only get the association between variables.

Part 2: Research question

Whats the relationship between a movies rating on IMDB and its audience score on Rotten Tomatoes.Whats more, can we use the audience score on Rotten Tomatoes to estimate its rating on IMDB?
Do the two websites share common valus to adjust a movies? I think a good movie shoule be marked as good across different groups of peoples.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

lets plot the relationship between audience score on Rotten Tomatoes and Rating on IMDB.
here are the variables:
  • imdb_rating: rating on IMDB
  • audience_score: score on Rotten Tomatoes. 
    • ggplot(movies, aes(x = audience_score, y = imdb_rating)) + geom_point() + stat_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)


    We can see a strong, positive, lieanr relationship.
    Next, lets compute the correlation and the R2.

    movies %>% summarise(correlation = cor(imdb_rating, audience_score), R2 = cor(imdb_rating, audience_score)^2)
    ## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   correlation        R2
##         <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1   0.8648652 0.7479917
    The correlation and the R2 is prety heigh. It means about 74.8% of the variability in the imdb_rating is explained by the audience.

    When fitting a least squares line, we generally require linearity, nearly normall residuals, constant variability and independent obervations.

    lets cheek it now.
    Base on the scatter plot about imdb_rating and audience_socre, we can find there is a linear trend.

    Now lets check the nearly normal residuals assumption. 
    ml_audience = lm(imdb_rating ~ audience_score, data = movies)
hist(ml_audience$residuals)

    qqnorm(ml_audience$residuals)
qqline(ml_audience$residuals)


    The residuals appears to be a little left skewed, but still normal.

    Now lets check the constant variability assumoption. 
    ggplot(ml_audience, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point()


    The variance is approximately constant.

    Now lets check the independent observations assumption.

    lets plot the residuals versus its index. (Plotting residuals in the order that their corresponding observations were collected helps identify connections between successive observations.)

    plot(ml_audience$residuals)

    The data is randomly sampled movies. And base on the residuals plot, Its obvious that the data is not time series data.

    conclusion: there is a strong, positive, linear relationship between imdb_rating and audience_score. And we can use audience_score to predict the imdb_rating.

    Part 4: Modeling

    Full model variables runtime, thrt_rel_year, thtr_rel_month, imdb_num_votes, audience_score, best_dir_win, top_200_box.

    Excluded variables:
    I think the critics_score(critics score on Rotten Tomatoes) can be a helpful variable for this model. But the critics_score may correlate with other variables.
    lets check it.

    ggpairs(movies, columns = c(14, 16, 18))

    The critics_score and audience_score are collinear. Since collinearity complicates model estimation, we exclude the critics_score variables. * * *



    model selection method: backward elimination with the p-value approach.
    reson:I care about understanding which variables are statistically significant predictors of the imdb_rating variable, so the p-value approach is suitable.
    lets begain with the full model.

    ml_multi = lm(imdb_rating ~ runtime + thtr_rel_year + thtr_rel_month  +  imdb_num_votes + audience_score + best_dir_win + top200_box, data = movies)
summary(ml_multi)

    model diagnostics: Multiple regression method generally depend on the following four assumptions:
  • 1,the residuals of the moudel are nearly normal.
  • 2,the variability of the residuals is nearly constant.
  • 3,the residuals are independent.
  • 4,each variable is linear to the outcome.


    • First, lets check the whether the residuals of the moudel are nearly normal. 
    hist(ml_multi$residuals)

    qqnorm(ml_multi$residuals)
qqline(ml_multi$residuals)

    The residuals also appears to be a littel left skewed, but still normal.
    Second, check the constant variablility of residuals assuption. 
    plot(abs(ml_multi$residuals) ~ ml_multi$fitted.values)

    The residuals variance is approximately constant.
    Next, check whether the residuals are independent.

    Lets plot the residuals versus its index.

    plot(ml_multi$residuals)

    Since the data is comprised of randomly sampled movies. And base on the residuals plot, the data is obvious not time series data. This assuption appears to met.
    last,lets check the each variable is linearly to the outcome assuption. 
    movies_for_plot <- movies %>% filter(!is.na(runtime),!is.na(imdb_num_votes),!is.na(audience_score))
plot(ml_multi$residuals ~ movies_for_plot$runtime)

    plot(ml_multi$residuals ~ movies_for_plot$imdb_num_votes)

    plot(ml_multi$residuals ~ movies_for_plot$audience_score)

    The residuals versus imdb_num_votes appears to be a fan shaped pattern. The other residuals plots appears to be no pattern. SO this assumption is a little violated, but it do not go too far.

    interpretation:
    runtime: For each additional minute in runtime, the average rating on IMDB is expected to be an additional 5.476e-03 rate on average.
    imdb_num_vote: The mode predicts a 5.508e-07 increase in the rating on IMDB for ecah additional number in votes on IMDB, all else held constant.
    audience_score: The mode predicts a 4.453e-03 increase in the rating on IMDB for ecah additional audience score on Rotten Tomatoes, all else held constant.

    Part 5: Prediction

    Lets predict the la la land.
    Here are some infomation:
    runtime: 2h8mins
    imdb_rating: 8.2
    imdb_num_votes: 296641
    audience_score:82
    Now lets predict this movie.

    la_la_land <- data.frame(runtime = 2*60 + 8, imdb_num_votes = 296641, audience_score = 82)
predict(ml_multi, la_la_land, interval = "prediction", level = 0.95)
    ##        fit     lwr      upr
## 1 7.619812 6.57711 8.662514

    The prediction interval with 95% confidence interval is (6.57711, 8.662514).
    Interpretation:we are 95% confidence that the rating on IMDB of la la land is between 6.57711 and 8.662514.
    reference:
    http://www.imdb.com/title/tt3783958/?ref_=nv_sr_1
    https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/la_la_land
